🍎 Topic 2: SQL Joins (with Schema + Business Context)

Each question below mirrors what Apple’s Global BI or Data Platform teams ask —
you’ll see how joins are used to derive insights from multiple related tables.

🟢 Q1. Total Spend per Customer (INNER JOIN)
🧱 Table Schema

customers

customer_id	customer_name	region_id
1	Alice	1
2	Bob	2
3	Charlie	1

orders

order_id	customer_id	amount
101	1	100
102	1	150
103	2	200
🎯 Question

Find each customer's total spend.

✅ Query
SELECT
    c.customer_name,
    SUM(o.amount) AS total_spend
FROM customers c
JOIN orders o
    ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id
GROUP BY c.customer_name;

🟢 Q2. Customers Who Have Not Placed Any Orders (LEFT JOIN)
🧱 Table Schema

Same as above.

🎯 Question

Find all customers who haven’t placed any orders yet.

✅ Query
SELECT
    c.customer_name
FROM customers c
LEFT JOIN orders o
    ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id
WHERE o.order_id IS NULL;

🟢 Q3. Orders Without a Valid Customer (RIGHT JOIN)
🧱 Table Schema

orders

order_id	customer_id	amount
201	10	100

customers

customer_id	customer_name
1	Alice
2	Bob
🎯 Question

Find all orders that reference a customer not in the customers table.

✅ Query
SELECT
    o.order_id,
    o.customer_id,
    o.amount
FROM customers c
RIGHT JOIN orders o
    ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id
WHERE c.customer_id IS NULL;

🟠 Q4. Manager–Employee Relationship (SELF JOIN)
🧱 Table Schema

employees

emp_id	emp_name	manager_id
1	Alice	NULL
2	Bob	1
3	Charlie	1
4	David	2
🎯 Question

Show each employee with their manager's name.

✅ Query
SELECT
    e.emp_name AS employee,
    m.emp_name AS manager
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN employees m
    ON e.manager_id = m.emp_id;

🟠 Q5. Customers in the Same City (SELF JOIN)
🧱 Table Schema

customers

customer_id	customer_name	city
1	Alice	London
2	Bob	Paris
3	Charlie	London
🎯 Question

List all unique pairs of customers living in the same city.

✅ Query
SELECT
    a.customer_name AS customer1,
    b.customer_name AS customer2,
    a.city
FROM customers a
JOIN customers b
    ON a.city = b.city AND a.customer_id < b.customer_id;

